g.text: ISR Stack Frame Layout: Ring 0 vs Ring 3 Interrupt

p.strong: How the CPU builds the frame:

ol.li: Saves EFLAGS, CS, EIP onto current kernel stack
For exceptions with error code: pushes error_code
Jumps to ISR stub stub pushes vector (+ dummy 0 if no error code)
Calls C handler with frame pointer = ESP

p.strong: Ring 3 Ring 0 (privilege transition via interrupt gate):

ol.li: CPU checks IDT gate DPL CPL; checks CPL > gate.DPL (transition needed)
CPU reads TSS.ESP0 (ring-0 stack pointer) from kernel_tss
CPU switches SS:ESP to TSS.SS0:TSS.ESP0 (kernel stack)
CPU pushes user_SS, user_ESP, EFLAGS, user_CS, user_EIP
Remainder identical to ring-0 path (steps 37 above)

ul.li: Ring 0: pops EIP, CS, EFLAGS (3 values, 12 bytes)
Ring 3: pops EIP, CS, EFLAGS, user_ESP, user_SS (5 values, 20 bytes) CS.DPL > CPL triggers the extra pop and SS/ESP restore

div.p: FRAME_FROM_RING3(frame): (frame->cs & 0x3) == 3 bit 0 and 1 of CS = RPL; if RPL=3 then user_esp/user_ss are valid
No privilege transition ESP stays on kernel stack sizeof = 68 bytes (17 4)
Privilege transition: ring 3 ring 0 CPU reads TSS.ESP0 for kernel stack sizeof = 76 bytes (19 4)
